03870nam a22007215i 9780691188058DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911880587 a10.1515/97806911880582doi  a(DE-B1597)501930  a(OCoLC)1076457529  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJA71b.B76 2001eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320/.01/12231 aBrown, Wendy, eauthor.10aPolitics Out of History /cWendy Brown. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tONE. INTRODUCTION -- tTWO. SYMPTOMS -- tTHREE. DESIRE -- tFOUR. POWER -- tFIVE. POLITICS -- tSIX. DEMOCRACY -- tSEVEN. FUTURES -- tNOTES -- tINDEX  aWhat happens to left and liberal political orientations when faith in progress is broken, when both the sovereign individual and sovereign states seem tenuous, when desire seems as likely to seek punishment as freedom, when all political conviction is revealed as contingent and subjective? Politics Out of History is animated by the question of how we navigate the contemporary political landscape when the traditional compass points of modernity have all but disappeared. Wendy Brown diagnoses a range of contemporary political tendencies--from moralistic high-handedness to low-lying political despair in politics, from the difficulty of formulating political alternatives to reproaches against theory in intellectual life--as the consequence of this disorientation. Politics Out of History also presents a provocative argument for a new approach to thinking about history--one that forsakes the idea that history has a purpose and treats it instead as a way of illuminating openings in the present by, for example, identifying the haunting and constraining effects of past injustices unresolved. Brown also argues for a revitalized relationship between intellectual and political life, one that cultivates the autonomy of each while promoting their interlocutory potential. This book will be essential reading for all who find the trajectories of contemporary liberal democracies bewildering and are willing to engage readings of a range of thinkers--Freud, Marx, Nietzsche, Spinoza, Benjamin, Derrida--to rethink democratic possibility in our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aLiberalism. 0aPolitical sciencexHistory. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aProgress. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188058zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188058.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN